  "verdict": "NO: Geometric constraint does NOT create cross-prime dependence. Observed MI on all diagonal types is ~0 (order 1e-7 to 1e-6 bits), consistent with perfect CRT independence. Negative z-scores mean the data is MORE independent than shuffled nulls (which have upward finite-sample bias). The 2D grid structure does not couple prime fibers. Independence is absolute even on geometric subsets.",
  "theoretical_note": "By CRT, for consecutive integers, mod-p and mod-q residues are independent when gcd(p,q)=1. A linear diagonal on a row-major grid selects integers in arithmetic progression (step = row_width \u00b1 k), which preserves uniform cycling through residue classes. Hence CRT independence should hold exactly on any single diagonal line, and approximately when aggregating multiple diagonals of the same slope."
